The '''2019 Davis Cup''' will be the 108th edition of the [[Davis Cup]], a tournament between national teams in men's tennis. It is sponsored by [[BNP Paribas]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.daviscup.com/en/news/225951.aspx|title=Davis Cup - ITF confirms 2017 Davis Cup dates|work=DavisCup.com|date=2016-03-14}}</ref>

For this edition, the format of the cup will be changed.<ref name=format>{{cite web |title=Historic Davis Cup reforms approved at AGM |url=https://www.daviscup.com/en/news/290055.aspx |website=Daviscup.com |accessdate=16 September 2018}}</ref> The main modification is the World Group taking place at one location and in one week, with eighteen teams divided in six round-robin groups of three teams each, with the winners of the groups and the two best second places advancing to quarterfinals. The series between the teams in this stage will feature two singles matches and one doubles match, instead of the best-of-5 series, with the matches changing from best of 5 sets to best of 3. As the World Group will now take place as one single tournament, this event has been named as the Davis Cup Finals. The lower zone groups I and II will be composed of single ties deciding promotion or relegation.{{cn|date=October 2018}}

==Davis Cup Finals==

''Date: 18–24 November 2019''<ref name="date and surface">{{cite news|url=https://www.daviscup.com/en/news/295131.aspx|title=Inaugural Davis Cup finals to be staged on 18-24 November|work=Daviscup.com|date=2018-10-17}}</ref><br> 
''Venue: [[Caja Mágica]] in Madrid, Spain''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.daviscup.com/en/news/292906.aspx|title=Madrid chosen as host city for 2019, 2020 Davis Cup finals|work=Daviscup.com|date=2018-09-27}}</ref> 
The finals will be played on hard court.<ref name="date and surface"/>

18 nations will take part in the Finals, formerly known as World Group. The qualification is as following:
* 4 semifinalists of the previous edition
* 12 winners of a qualifier round, in February 2019
* 2 wild card teams

