{{Expand Spanish|Batalla del vino|topic=culture|date=March 2009}}
[[File:Batalla del Vino - Haro - La Rioja.jpg|thumb|right|280px|Haro Wine Festival]]
'''Haro Wine Festival''' is a festival in the town of [[Haro, La Rioja|Haro]] in the [[La Rioja (autonomous community)|La Rioja]] region of northern [[Spain]]. It is held every year in the summer and involves a ''Batalla de Vino'' (Battle of Wine) where wines are poured at each other from buckets.

The celebration takes place on June 29, the day of the patron saint San Pedro. The day begins at 9:00 am, with a procession of people old and young,all carrying jugs, bottles, botas and other types of containers filled with red wine. Led by the town's mayor, on horseback, the procession winds through the town to the Cliffs of Bilibio, where a mass is celebrated at the Hermitage of San Felices de Bilibio.  After the mass a true free-for-all begins, with everyone tossing wine on each other until all are soaked from head to foot. Then at noon everyone returns to town to celebrate at the Plaza de la Paz, followed by bullfights in the town's bullring.  But the bullfights are only for the youth, and the "bulls" are actually just heifers. Also, none of the heifers are killed. Also, no bull-fighting happens at all. <ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/europe/spain/735093/Grapes--of-mirth.html | publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited | work=The Telegraph | title=Grapes of mirth | date=2006-10-05}}</ref>

